The world born of September 11
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th anniversary of the terrorist attacks of September 11, 2001, in the United States.
On that day, 19 terrorists took control of four commercial aircraft, crashed two of them into the towers of the World Trade Center in New York, struck the Pentagon with a third, and crashed a fourth plane in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believed was the White House or another American government building in Washington, D.C.
All the hijackers were from the Middle East, and 15 were from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of an operation planned, organized, and carried out by Al-Qaeda (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
By the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women, and children were reported dead, and more than 6,000 were injured.
Most were American, though citizens from over a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that September 11 had brought about an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other Al-Qaeda-led attacks followed, notably several explosions in Madrid's trains in March 2004, then the attack perpetrated in London's public transport in July 2005.
The terrorists who pledged allegiance to Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and carried out a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to ram pedestrians).
Nevertheless, neither the United States nor any of their allies have ever suffered an attack of comparable magnitude to those of September 11 – which are without precedent.
It follows, therefore, that we must ask: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference did September 11 make?
Has history changed, and if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why the terrorists did not manage to carry out other major attacks.
After the American invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaeda lost its sanctuary.
Almost all governments around the world have implemented security procedures making it harder for potential terrorists to access airports and airplanes.
Governments have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the few areas in which states, often in disagreement, are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is now also a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political ends – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments should not make a distinction between terrorists and those who provide them sanctuary and support.
Gone are the days when individuals and groups ready to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters.
It is not about asserting that terrorism has ceased to claim tens of thousands of lives each year.
However, almost all attacks take place in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within the context of ongoing conflicts (primarily in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks, like those of September 11, targeting major powers.
Terrorism is increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaeda survived the elimination of Bin Laden by American special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the September 11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no resolution to the problem on the horizon.
The possibility of another September 11 cannot be ruled out either, although the U.S. government recently stated that the "greatest terrorist threat" to the country exists domestically.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army formulated after its failed assassination attempt on British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in 1984, "Today, we did not have the luck, but remember that it is enough for us to have luck just once."
"You will always need to."
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists could obtain nuclear material, or manage to manufacture and use a biological or chemical weapon, in which case terrorism could define the era.
For now, that is not the case.
September 11 nonetheless marked a historic turning point, with a profound impact on American foreign policy over the past twenty years.
If the attacks did not lead to an era of worldwide terrorism, they did indeed give rise to the famous war on terror, with significant consequences for the behavior of the United States around the world, America's image in the eyes of the world, and how many Americans came to view their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Soon after the September 11 attacks, the United States offered the Taliban, who controlled the Afghan government at the time, a choice: hand over the Al-Qaeda suspects about to leave the country and responsible for the September 11 attacks, or risk losing their rule.
After the Taliban refused to hand over Al-Qaeda's leaders, American intelligence and military collaborated with an unstructured coalition of Afghan tribes, called the Northern Alliance, to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States contributed to the formation of a successor government that took control of most of the country.
This control, however, was never total or uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaeda sought refuge in neighboring Pakistan, where they gradually rebuilt their strength and resumed military operations against the new government that had replaced them.
On their side, the United States did not sufficiently work to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, America strengthened its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, essentially becoming a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, the United States' intervention in Afghanistan mobilized over 100,000 American soldiers.
Over more than twenty years, the cost of operations has reached over $2 trillion, with over 2,300 American lives lost, and tens of thousands among the Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The American presence deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy and fueled opposition to the United States, while the Taliban proved more tenacious than America, which in 2020 had lost all will to fight in a conflict destined to end in an indefinite stalemate.
The war on terror also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily if September 11 had not occurred.
The attacks certainly reinforced his tendency to want to signal to the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had formulated during the Vietnam War, a "giant impotent and pitiful."
This led some members of the administration (primarily Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse to take the risk of terrorists acquiring weapons of mass destruction, which the Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein seemed to possess (though this turned out not to be the case) according to most protagonists.
Others aimed to spread democracy in Iraq, then throughout the entire Middle East, believing that such an approach was not only achievable but would also make the region much less likely to produce and support terrorists.
Triggered in March 2003, the Iraq war did not unfold as hoped or planned by the Bush administration, as well as by many congressional members (including Senator Joe Biden) and world leaders who had approved it.
The United States were not prepared for the essential events to come.
The military victories initially allowed for the ousting of the government, but soon gave way to widespread unrest and violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army and exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs worsened an already chaotic situation.
More fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, demonstrated the limits of what military force can achieve at a reasonable cost and within a reasonable timeframe.
In the end, the United States was forced to strengthen its military presence, bringing it to nearly 170,000 soldiers, to preserve the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability has been achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but at a much higher human cost: over 4,000 American soldiers killed, far more wounded, and an explosive rise in suicide rates among American military personnel (from Iraq as well as Afghanistan).
This total excludes, moreover, the deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for whom estimates vary widely, but which number certainly runs into the hundreds of thousands.
The war in Iraq also weakened the United States in other ways.
No evidence ever showed Iraq's involvement in the September 11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for military intervention without UN approval—to eliminate Saddam's weapons of mass destruction—turned out to be based on no real foundation.
Images of American soldiers abusing Iraqi prisoners have further tarnished the country's reputation.
Furthermore, a self-warring Iraq has become synonymous with Iran emerging as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if Israel is considered).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also proven to be two major strategic diversions.
While the United States became deeply involved in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking major powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted against the United States both in Europe and East Asia, owing to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia, as well as a stronger and more assertive China.
The global war on terrorism could not provide and did not provide the United States with a compass in its approach to foreign policy regarding a renewed great power rivalry.
The wars launched in the wake of September 11 also had important domestic consequences for the United States.
They shook the confidence in a country that had emerged from the Cold War with historically unprecedented overwhelming power, and undermined the national unity that had surfaced immediately after the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars have further fueled opposition to a major and enduring global role for the United States, giving rise to a new isolationist trend.
Similarly, this propensity for warfare, coupled with the global financial crisis of 2007-2009 and its economic repercussions, severely impacted Americans' trust in elites, thereby fueling the rise of populist sentiments that, among other consequences, contributed to Donald Trump's rise to power.
Today's America is more divided than ever internally, and increasingly less willing to pursue this form of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of World War II, and which has largely benefited Americans as well as many others.
With hindsight, we can now consider September 11 as a harbinger of what was to come: less globalization of terrorism than the fears of globalization.
The attacks conveyed the message that distance and borders mattered little in the age of globalization.
Nothing remains local for long nowadays, whether it be terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis rooted in poor American financial management.
We are currently all confronted with a pandemic virus that has killed several million people since its appearance in China in December 2019.
The fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves that devastate many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, itself the cumulative effect of human activity that releases unimaginable amounts of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era ushered in by recent events concludes a cycle, marking the 20th anniversary of the American intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were swiftly removed from power; in recent weeks, they reclaimed it just as easily.
It is too early to know if the Taliban will revert to their old habits by once again becoming a sanctuary for terrorism, and if terrorists from around the world will take pride in their victory over America and its allies.
What we do know, however, is that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that in turn already determines it.
